# SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0-or-later
#
# Pin for s7.c / s7.h, sourced by krudd/third_party/sync.sh. This is the one
# place the s7 pin lives — see VENDOR.md for the fetch mechanism and license
# rationale.
#
# s7 is no longer tracked against upstream here: the org's kruddage/s7 repo
# (https://github.com/kruddage/s7) re-cuts upstream S7 Scheme releases as our
# own GitHub Releases and owns the wasm KRUDD-LOCAL PATCH. The engine pins one
# of those releases below; the committed s7.c/s7.h are a checksum-verified
# cache of that release's source assets.
#
# Re-vendoring: bump S7_RELEASE to a newer kruddage/s7 release and update
# S7_C_SHA256/S7_H_SHA256 to that release's assets, then delete the committed
# s7.c/s7.h and re-run sync.sh (or krudd.sh) — it downloads the pinned release
# assets, fails loudly if these checksums weren't updated to match, and the
# result should be committed back to the repo.
#
# NOTE: the wasm-only KRUDD-LOCAL PATCH (search it in s7.c; rationale in
# VENDOR.md "Local patches") now lives in kruddage/s7, so the release assets
# ship pre-patched and S7_C_SHA256 below is the checksum of the release's
# (already-patched) s7.c. There is no separate re-apply step in this repo
# anymore — picking a kruddage/s7 release that carries the patch is the whole
# job. Verify in a browser after any bump; the native suite cannot see a
# wasm-only signature mismatch. S7_VERSION/S7_DATE are upstream provenance.

S7_VERSION="10.8"
S7_DATE="17-Apr-2024"
S7_RELEASE="v10.8-krudd.1"

S7_C_URL="https://github.com/kruddage/s7/releases/download/$S7_RELEASE/s7.c"
S7_H_URL="https://github.com/kruddage/s7/releases/download/$S7_RELEASE/s7.h"

S7_C_SHA256="2a7f4438a2f82d3d2e05f9dd55ad345034fcb53ae2a34eaa287e75868e04f531"
S7_H_SHA256="4054fd2b3dfd2416a87312e8ae78f5dbb4ec9c02031b10030634d555b27bc826"
